Metabolics Experiment

We filtered the metabolic data and removed any trial where the miss distance at endpoint was greater than 10 cm, the movement duration was less than 0.2 seconds, or the reaction time was greater than 0.50 s.This removed 13 out of 15975 original data poitns.

Gross metabolic power.

Parameter estimates are showing as mean +- standard error. The columns are for without the subject mass coefficient, and with a mass coefficient on the effort model. Subj Mass Coef is the subject mass exponent.

The no_mass_coef model is as follows: \[ \dot{e} = a+\frac{bm^c}{T_m^d} \]

The Subject mass model times a1 is as follows: \[ \dot{e} = a*Body Mass^{f}+\frac{bm^c}{T_m^d} \]

The effective mass model times a1 is as follows: \[ \dot{e} = a*Effective\, Mass^{f}+\frac{bm^c}{T_m^d} \]

Probablity Modeling

Section for probability of sucess in just 2a and 2b without 1

Probability of success using experiment 1

This plot shows the prbability of success as a function of movement duration and mass.

The probability function for the circle target is: \[ ln\left(\frac{P_i}{1-P_i}\right) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_1 + \beta_2 x_2 \] Which leads to \[ P(Success|m,T) = \frac{1}{1+e^{-(\beta_0) - (\beta_1)m - (\beta_2)T}} \]

Beta coefficient for the inverse logit function to predict probability of success.

Utility Modeling

This plot below shows individual subjects and their utility fits.

Utility fits by subject.

Table for the coefficients in Utility Modeling

We next fitted a utility model by altering \(\alpha\) to try and predict the movement durations seen in 2a,b,c.

The utility function that is fit for these next plots is below. \(T_r\) and \(T_m\) are the reaction time and movement duration. \(P(R|m,t)\) is determined from the section above, probability alpha modeling. \(a\), \(b\), \(c\), \(d\) are determined from the metabolic data. Resting rate is shown by \(a_0\), and $ a_0 $ = 73.527. The parameters a, b, c, and d are shown in @ref(tab:effort_mod_tab).

\[J = \frac{\alpha P(R|m,T) -\left( a_0 T_r + a T_m + \frac{bm^c}{T_m^d} \right)}{T_r+T_m}\]

\(T_r\) and \(T_m\) are the reaction time and movement duration. Using the values from experiment 2a,b,c, we can optimize the error of the prediction by altering \(\alpha\).
